problems.description:
Write parameterized tests to validate input across multiple cases.

```java
class PasswordValidatorTest {
    private final PasswordValidator validator = new PasswordValidator();

    @ParameterizedTest
    @CsvSource({
        "StrongPass1!, true",   // valid
        "weakpass,   false",    // no uppercase/digit/special
        "Short1!,    false",    // too short (< 8 chars)
        "NoSpecial1, false",    // missing special char
        "NOLOWER1!,  false",    // missing lowercase
        "NoDigit!!,  false"     // missing digit
    })
    void validate(String password, boolean expected) {
        assertEquals(expected, validator.isValid(password));
    }

    @ParameterizedTest
    @MethodSource("edgeCaseProvider")
    void validate_edgeCases(String password, boolean expected, String reason) {
        assertEquals(expected, validator.isValid(password), reason);
    }
    static Stream<Arguments> edgeCaseProvider() {
        return Stream.of(
            Arguments.of(null, false, "null should be invalid"),
            Arguments.of("", false, "empty should be invalid"),
            Arguments.of("A1!" + "a".repeat(100), true, "long password should be valid")
        );
    }
}
```

**Key insight:** `@ParameterizedTest` runs the same test logic with different inputs. `@CsvSource` for simple cases. `@MethodSource` for complex objects. Reduces duplicate test code dramatically.

